The South African Reserve Bank (SARB) is set to announce the first repo rate decision for the year today with economists predicting that the rate will remain unchanged. JOHANNESBURG - The Reserve Bank has cut the repo rate by 25 basis points to 6.25-percent. Reserve Bank Governor, Lesetja Kganyago announced the repo rate on Thursday. "Against this backdrop, the MPC decided to reduce the repurchase rate by 25 basis points. The decision was unanimous," said Kganyago. The forecast 2020 and 2021 have also "decreased to 1.2-percent (from 1.4%-percent) and 1.6-percent (from 1.7-percent), respectively, due to lower growth than previously expected in the third and fourth quarters. The GDP forecast for 2022 is 1.9-percent." READ: Repo rate remains unchanged Last year, the Reserve Bank kept the interest rate unchanged at 6.5-percent. However, the Reserve Bank indicated that a repo cut was on the cards for 2020.